For the emission wavelength at 618 nm, the maximum excitation peak at 330 nm in the excitation spectrum of Eu3+-DTPA-bis(AMC) is basically consistent with the maximum absorption peak at 325 nm in the UV–vis absorption spectrum of DTPA-bis(AMC), which indicates that the energy absorption of Eu3+-DTPA-bis(AMC) mainly comes from the fluorophore AMC. It can be seen from the Fig. 1a that under excitation at 330 nm, the emission spectrum of Eu3+-DTPA-bis (AMC) is mainly divided into two parts: the blue-violet part of 350–475 nm and the orange-red part of 580–720 nm. The blue-violet part is attributed to the fluorescence emission of the AMC group, and the orange-red light part is attributed to the sensitized europium ion. The organic fluorophore can sensitize Eu3+ through a chelating agent, and then emit the characteristic emission peak group of Eu3+ (5D0 → 7F
                           J
                        ) (J = 0, 1, 2, 3, 4) at 579, 592, 618, 650 and 700 nm respectively[52,53], of which 5D0 → 7F2 is the most important red emission peak (fwhm = 7 nm) [54,55]. The Stokes shift of Eu3+-DTPA-bis(AMC) is up to 288 nm. In order to better understand the stoichiometric ratio of Eu3+ to the ligand DTPA-bis(AMC), the job curve experiment was carried out (in Fig. 1b). When the mole fraction was 0.52, the fluorescence emission intensity at 618 nm reached the maximum, indicating that the molar ratio of Eu3+ to DTPA-bis(AMC) was 1:1. In HRMS, when one equivalent of Eu3+ was added to the DTPA-bis(AMC) solution, a peak at m/z 856.13453 appeared, which could be ascribed to [Eu3+-DTPA-bis(AMC)-H]+. This further demonstrated that Eu3+ and DTPA-bis(AMC) formed a complex in a molar ratio of 1:1.
